[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Just think about it. Only 4 years ago AI generated 3D model was looking like this. And today it looks like this. A huge leap forward. But where did it actually start? And what actually happened'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in between? There are so many interesting facts about this evolution you don\'t know. So sit tight, grab your snacks and I welcome you on Evolution of 3D AI Generators. Moving from hand-built'

[00:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '3D to AI generated 3D has been one of the biggest shifts computer graphics has ever seen. So where it all begins. It starts in 2015. And the main question'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dot sign was how do you even explain to neural network what a 3D shape is? And that was actually a big one. Researchers tried three main formats.'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'First, voxel. Think Lego cubes filling a virtual box. Simple, but the memory cost explodes the moment you want detail. Imagine small detail, more cubes.'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And so forth. Next one, point clouds. Million of dots floating in the space. Lightweight, but no actual surface you can paint or texture. That was the problem. And the polygonal meshes.'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The standard grid every 3D model is made of, but very hard for AI to invent from scratch. Especially at that time. From 2015 onwards, the voxel approach dominated.'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We saw papers like 3D shape, nets and 3DGAN. But voxels run straight into the curse of dimensionality I mentioned before. Doubling the detail means'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '8 times more cubes. And the mass collapsed. The real breakthrough came in 2019 to 2020 with implicit fields. New architecture.'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Instead of drawing the 3D models directly, the AI learned to answer one yes or no question. Is this point inside the object or outside? Ask it for every point in space and'

[02:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shape emerges at any resolution you want. No grid limits. Around the same time came differentiable rendering. A trick that let AI improve its 3D shape by comparing its'

[02:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'virtual shadow to a real photographer. Make the shape, render it as 2D image. See where the image is wrong. Nudge the shape. Repeat thousand times. This unlocked the landmark'

[02:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'method called Nerf, which taught a neural network to memorize a full 3D scene from a handful of photos. And in 2022, there was Dreamfusion, which could'

[02:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generate a 3D object directly from a text prompt. Those were beautiful results for researchers and absolutely unuseful for professionals. The output was a reminding, fine-looking blob'

[02:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with chaotic geometry. No UV whatsoever. No realistic materials. And the cleanup usually takes more time than build this shape from scratch.'

[03:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Approaching 2022, things started to get interesting. So up to the end of 2022, the main obstacle was a catastrophic shortage of 3D training data. There were tens of'

[03:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'millions of labeled 2D images on the internet, but real 3D models were rare and expensive to make. However, still in 2022, Google published the Dreamfusion paper, and they introduced'

[03:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the new method called Score Destillation Sampling, or SDS. The idea was extremely clever. There were already brilliant 2D image generators, like Imagine.'

[03:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So what if we use one of the 2D AI as a teacher for a 3D model? SDS works exactly like that. Picture a blind sculptor with a sighted art critic.'

[03:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The sculptor, the 3D model, shapes something at random, then shows it from different angles to the critic, which is 2D AI. The critic says, from this angle, it doesn\'t look like a chirp.'

[04:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Add a backrest. The sculptor adjusts, and we repeat that thousands of times, and the object looks correct from every angle. But still, it was just a workaround for the fact that nobody had enough 3D training'

[04:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'data yet. And it worked. The same month, NVIDIA releases Magic 3D, a two-step refinement of the same idea. First, a nerf made a rough draft, then'

[04:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a tool called DMTet, which converts a messy implicit shape into a clean polygonal mesh, sharpen it into a high -detail final model. And by the way, Magic 3D, it\'s the'

[04:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'time when it caught more attention. That was impressive to see, like, I mean, something happening in this direction. And we already saw GPT-23, and I was really excited. In about the same'

[04:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'time, OpenAI shipped Point E, fast texture 3D, but it was about point clouds. No real surface, but it was extremely fast. And you can see it looks like a bunch of dots, which'

[05:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they are. But the real catalyst for the future commercial boom was the release of Objectiverse 1.0, a dataset of more than 100,000 labeled 3D objects, free for'

[05:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'researchers. And that was truly amazing. For the first time, there was enough 3D data to train a real 3D model directly, one that could produce an object in one'

[05:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shot instead of slowly optimizing it, like it was with SDS approach. Around the same time, Common Sense Machines began building its platform for turning 3D images into the 3D game world'

[05:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'simulation. They were one of the first. And the same year, Hunion from Tencent actually builds up the researcher team. In 2023, the focus shifted.'

[05:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Academic experiments could take hours of compute per object, but the industry now wanted to feed forward networks. The one short kind, like input on an image, output as a 3D model in seconds,'

[06:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'no slow optimization loop. And in March 2023, the popular 3D design platform Spline, which I was actually using at that time, launched the Alpha of Spline AI,'

[06:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one of the first attempts to put generative features directly inside a browser editor with no separate software needed. But truly historical moments happened when Objectiverse Excel released.'

[06:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It brought 10.2 million labeled 3D data, which is 100 times more than it was in previous Objectiverse 1 .0. It has photogrammetry scans, professional models, hand'

[06:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '-built assets, all mixed together. This was finally enough data to train true foundation models. One of them actually was 0123XL, and you can see what results'

[07:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it was providing at that time. But the thing is, everyone realized that the scale of training data works well, as the same way it worked for ChatGPT, more data, smarter LLM. But in 2023, we'

[07:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get another historical pivot with releasing 3D Gaussian Splatting, also known as 3DGS. NERF rendered a scene by slowly tracing rays through a volume, which'

[07:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'was expensive, and 3DGS did something completely different. It painted the scene as millions of tiny glowing droplets, semi-transparent blobs, each one a few pixels wide.'

[07:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'A GPU could render that almost instantly. Same realism, a fraction of compute. It became the foundation of a whole new wave of new AI tools. In August that year, quite famous South Korean'

[07:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'company called NCSoft actually announces Varco LLM, a set of foundation models that they were about to build, especially focusing on game development. Yes, this started like'

[08:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in 2023 with Here\'s the News, but the first 3D AI model only saw light in 2025 in December. But at that time, Common Sense Machines started publicly tested their photo'

[08:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to 3D platform. That was probably the first opportunity to anyone to go and test it. In October 2023, the first version of MESH -E1 officially launched. Generation at that time'

[08:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'was taking about a minute, but the meshes looked like melted plastic, full of artifacts and had no clean topology. But still, it was quite impressive. It was also a big step into democratizing'

[08:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this technology. It was actually become accessible. Around the same time, there was Estonian startup called Alpha 3D, which was actually growing very, very fast, and they'

[08:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'were focusing on AR and was also one of the first to implement this. They showed crazy numbers in terms of growing revenue, which confirms the interest to this at that time. Then by the end'

[09:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of 2023, a new concept arrived. Large reconstruction models. Transformer networks, the same family as ChaiGPT, trained it to look at a single image and output compressed 3D representation'

[09:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'called a tree plane, a tree flat slices that together encode the full 3D shape. Five seconds, one image, a complete 3D model. Slow SDS optimization process'

[09:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'was suddenly absolutely obsolete. Also in 2023, Worst AI was founded, which later became Triple AI. So to summarize, by the end of 2023,'

[09:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'AI could generate the overall shape of the object, but the geometry inside was quite useless. Mesh was chaotic bunch of triangles with broken normals, no UV map, absolutely broken materials.'

[09:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So in 2024, companies started to target production ready assets. And at this point, there was a pivot. Instead of trying to continuously refine the model as it was with SDS, companies and researchers'

[10:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'start to train foundational 3D models that will understand the shape and build and think in three dimensions. Same process that happened to stable diffusion and'

[10:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mid-journey, but now in 3D volume. And in March that year, Triple AI in collaboration with Stability AI made an open academic breakthrough by releasing TripoSR. Built on LRM principles,'

[10:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'TripoSR could generate a 3D object from a single image in under a half a second on NVIDIA A100. Trained on a subset of observers, it became the new speed standard'

[10:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for open source 3D AI. That was a huge step forward. In February, Mesh launched Mesh 2 and in March, Mesh 2.5. The key innovation there was a texture editing and image to prompt.'

[11:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now you were able to upload your image and actually get the 3D model. In May 2024, DreamTech researchers introduced Direct3D, a cleaner, more accurate approach.'

[11:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Earlier methods rendered the object as 2D image first, then tried to recover the 3D from them. Direct3D skipped that step entirely. Two parts are D3D VAE that compressed 3D'

[11:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'objects into a tiny internal representation and D3D DIT that generates new shapes inside that compressed space via diffusion. The model now understood'

[11:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'volume directly. That\'s why it\'s called Direct3D. No blurry shapes, no drifting geometry, just stable, sharp results. In the same period, on May 8th, Autodesk'

[11:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'announced the research project called Bernini. And that was the first time industry leaders stepped into the game. We also will take part here. Bernini focused on functional 3D forms, accepting voxels,'

[12:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '2D images in point clouds as a prompt. Trained on a massive professional CAD dataset, 10 million shapes, it actually showed heavy industry interest in generative AI.'

[12:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Shifting focus from game art towards strict engineering. Through that summer, competition intensified. Triple AI shipped 1 .1 series, first time introducing multi-view inputs that allow you to'

[12:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'drop several images from different angles. And also they introduced smart low poly that automatically dropped the poly count later. In July, Meshi 3 Turbo arrived.'

[12:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In August, Meshi 4. The headline of Meshi 4 was remastered geometry. The model started to generate anatomically correct organic forms for characters and clean hard surfaces for'

[12:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mechanical objects. Cutting manual cleanup significantly. Right after, in September, Tripo launched Tripo 2 .0. And for several months, it was widely regarded as the strongest'

[13:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '3D generation model on the market. The jump was in the algorithm itself. Cleaner geometry, sharper edges, more controllable PBR materials there finally started to look like something.'

[13:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Faster generation, plus we first saw direct integration in like Unity. But biggest events yet to happen. On November 4 of 2024, Tencent released open source Funioon 3D 1'

[13:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '.0 along with the public technical reports. It was unified framework for text and image generation. And it caught fire on GitHub and Hugging Face over 3 million'

[13:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'downloads. Thanks to how stable results were. And it was really impressive. In December, the same year, Microsoft Research published Trellis, a real revolution. Trellis introduced a new'

[13:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'representation called SLAT, Structured Latent. In plain terms, it\'s a universal genetic code for an object that can be decoded into any required format and'

[14:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'north style render for photorealism, a 3D quotient for instant real-time rendering or classical polygonal mesh. Built on rectified flow transformers with 2 billion'

[14:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parameters. It allowed unprecedented flexibility and the ability to locally edit a model without retaining the whole network. At that time, already people started to experiment,'

[14:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'trying to launch Trellis, Funioon on local setups in just a bit later. And guys, before we continue, let me remind you that I just recently launched my first'

[14:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '3D AI course, a complete guide for beginners, solo devs to create 3D characters, props for your dream game. I spent a while figuring out the best workflow and now it\'s'

[14:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all packed. And two weeks with the release, I asked you guys to tell me your story, like what you\'re going to create, and I will give you a course for free. And it was amazing. I received a lot of comments, your amazing'

[15:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stories, and around 10 people got this course for free. Now I know there are more people who need it. So five more people who drop the story and tell what you do for a living,'

[15:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'why do you need this course, what do you want to create, will receive the course for free. All links in the description. In the beginning of 2025, local setups and Confio were popping up a lot. So by 2025, the'

[15:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basic problem of speed and volume was solved. It became accessible. The main challenge became the quality of mesh, accuracy and consistency with the prompt, resolution of'

[15:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the textures, and generally quality. And now things are getting way faster. Just look at this. In January 2025, Tencent released Huion 2.0, another open source model.'

[15:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And they introduced another innovation, the pipeline separation. There was two models, one model, Huion 3D DIT, that creates 3D model, and another model called Huion 3D Paint,'

[16:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which paints the model. That approach is still widely used. They also released Huion 3D 2MV, which was a multi-view model. That was the first open source model to'

[16:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'support multi-view. Same time, Tripo releasing Tripo 2.1. A very, very big jump for Tripo and probably the best model of 2025. As per my testing,'

[16:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there was improved PBR, there was noticeably cleaner retopology, you could control the polycount, they built up some infrastructure around it, which was amazing. At summer of 2025,'

[16:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we saw some companies start pivoting, such as Tencent actually released their first closed source Huion 2.5, which was only available on the cloud.'

[16:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'However, they were very generous, and on Chinese website, and still, you can actually go and use it for free. They give you free daily credits, which is amazing, but the model is closed source, and that was sort of'

[17:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an alarm. It was possible to new foundation model called Lattice. And at some point, it was meant to be open sourced, but you can see right now, it states that the company policy is'

[17:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'changed, and it will not be released anytime soon. However, as a compensation, they dropped Huion 2 .1, another open source model, and it was very, very good. It included PBR model,'

[17:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'VIE decoder, and all training code, which was amazing. It was not that good as 2.5, but was indeed very good. One more significant event, and I really remember'

[17:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that one. It was in May, 2025, we saw the paper called Spark Treaty. It was from researchers from Nanyang Technological University, the team that later found this high-tech treaty, and it was'

[17:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'quite a breakthrough. Since treaty space is mostly empty, and object only fills a small fraction of its bounding box, computing dense voxels grid was extremely faithful. The Spark Conv VIE'

[18:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'architecture and Spark cubes representation slashed compute cost almost in half. While keeping micro detail intact, the network learned to draw especially small'

[18:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'details like hair, thin fabric, some open surfaces that was previously no one did. And I remember I was looking at how cool is that, like how detailed it looked. And I even remember'

[18:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on hugging face, everyone were able to go and drop the image and test it out. That was absolutely cool. Same summer Meshify preview released, they added like multi-view supports, and they also started to'

[18:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'build up some infrastructure around it, like option to animate your character and rig it right away. I could not say it was useful, but it was definitely catchy, especially for marketing, which Meshet does probably even'

[19:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'too much. Few more releases that summer from Tencent was about Huion 3D Polygen. Polygen is a historical moment because they first showed that the AI'

[19:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generated mesh can actually look like mesh. And it was clean quads shape, and it was really amazing. It was only available at that time internally,'

[19:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and they only was showing the paper, but later that year, it will be available and Huion 3D Studio. And right now it available widely by API, any other thing. And another big drop was Huion World 1'

[19:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '.0, which was about creating the whole spaces. There was practically unusable, but it was really nice to have. The real leap forward happened in autumn 2025. Now get ready.'

[19:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The first big release was from 3PO, releasing 3PO 3.0, and that was really huge. They released ultra modes, they rise it up the poly count up to two millions, and the PBR was improved'

[20:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'significantly. It was really noticeable at that time. I first got taught that now is the time where you can drag and drop it to Unreal Engine game, and it will be used there. There was plenty of settings to control poly'

[20:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'count, so you can really create something like 10 to 20K, not millions. Almost same time Huion dropping Huion 3D 3 .0, which also increases the quality, pushes resolution to 1536p, 3.6'

[20:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'billion voxels. Huion getting very popular. On the hugging phase by that time, Huion 3D family crossed 2 .6 million downloads for variety of models.'

[20:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In October same year, out of a sudden, Void Dance, the developers of TikTok, dropping their first 3D AI model called Seed 3D 1 .1. It was a bit different. Unlike its competitors, Seed'

[20:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '3D was originally built as a foundation model for embodied AI and robotics. Yes, robotics. Why not? Its key innovation was about generation simulation ready assets fit physically calibrated'

[21:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'geometry. I was testing it at that time. I don\'t know what that means. Sounds cool, but doesn\'t look any better than other models that time. Another big player was conquering market, which are'

[21:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Demos Touch with their Hyper 3D Rodent. The first version of Rodent seen lights in starting 2024, but by releasing Rodent 2.0, they brought quite unique'

[21:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'innovation in the space. So it was based on new bang architecture with 10 billions per ammeter and their first to show like clean quad topology available for everyone.'

[21:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So they introduced quad based generation. That was a real salvation for professional 3D artists. However, in November, things start shaking. Meta released the open model Sam 3D, stands'

[21:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for Segment Anything 3D. It was built on top of revolutionary 2D segmentation work. Sam 3D objects and Sam 3D body added spatial scene understanding. This technology, by the'

[22:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'way, became basis for many startups, including the Common Sense Machine, which use same code for ultra fast and accurate depth analysis of 2D images. Unfortunately to Common Sense'

[22:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Machines, they announced that they will be closing in the early 2026. So effectively from January 2026, they are closed. Another company called Waiwa 3D joined the race'

[22:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in November 2025 with version 2. There were version 1 before, and they were focusing on incredibly detailed texture. But in version 2 in November 2025, they were first to introduce'

[22:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '8K PBR textures. And they are really like the namings like Ultima and Ultima Prime. And they also introduced some innovation called inside out texturing, trying to'

[22:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'solve the problem that all the models that time had is like leaving some holes in some deeper spaces. And they were quite successful on that. But there were also the most expensive guys'

[23:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on the market. There were not much time since Hunion dropped 3.0. In November, they already released 3 .1. And even though the version number look insignificant, but the update was actually noticeable.'

[23:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'They were first to introduce 8 multi-view supports. I still don\'t know if you ever will need that, but that was cool. But what really was useful for me at that time is that'

